        %h2.mtop10#section2Tips
          GAMSAT
          / %sup{style: "text-decoration:none"} ®
          Section 2 Essay Tips
        %p.mtop_zero
          Students often ask for specific pieces of advice to improve their essay writing, but such advice is most effective when it is specific to the individual. However, below are some general GAMSAT
          %sup ®
          Essay Writing Tips:

        %ol
          %li
            %a{href: "#Sentence_Structure"}
              Sentence Structure:
            Keep it concise and vary your sentence length to create cadence.
          %li
            %a{href: "#Rhetorical_Question"}
              The Rhetorical Question:
            Commonly overused by students. Make sure that you use it in the appropriate context.
          %li
            %a{href: "#Creating_Narrative"}
              Creating a Narrative:
            Keep the reader engaged and organise your writing as a series of causal steps.
          %li
            %a{href: "#Using_Analogies"}
              Using Analogies:
            A great literary technique to explain difficult concepts and to trigger emotions.

        .preparation_col.head_aftr_none
          %h3.mtop10.mbot20#Sentence_Structure
            Sentence Structure

          %p.mbot0 This aspect can be divided into the two following features:

          %ol.diffr_country.only_li_number
            %li
              %h4.mtop10
                %b Concision
              %p This is about those long wordy sentences which have several ideas packed into a single sentence. This veils the meaning of your sentence and makes your point difficult to decipher. As a rule, it is better to have just one idea within a single sentence. This makes it easier for the reader to understand your point in the sentence.

            %li
              %h4.mtop10
                %b Variety
              %p Sentence length should also have variety. Long sentences interspersed with short sentences create a good cadence for the essay. Cadence means rhythm, it is the way the words interact and show meaning. Lengthy sentences all together can make an essay monotonous and the meaning would be blurred. Think about making short and sharp statements before or after a long sentence. Variety in sentence length helps to put out your point in fewer words but with more impact.

        .preparation_col.head_aftr_none
          %h3.mtop10.mbot20#Rhetorical_Question
            The Rhetorical Question

          %p Use this as sparingly as you would with a future patient.

          %p
            At one point or another, most students feel the impulse to use a
            %a.green{href: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhetorical_question", target: :_blank}
              %strong
                rhetorical question
            = " – sometimes to the detriment of their essays. The GAMSAT"
            %sup ®
            Section 2 essay usually requires a response that is reflective or argumentative. The latter may engender the use of the rhetorical question to make an argument persuasive by asking the reader to consider a point, while providing an underlying response to their concern.

          %p As far as persuasion goes, the rhetorical question is quite effective but only when backed up with appropriate argumentation throughout the essay. Your argument itself should be the most effective feature of the essay. If the rhetorical question only distracts from the argument, it is better to use it carefully. A quick checklist can be used to confirm its appropriate use:


          .diffr_country
            %ul.cstm_list_style
              %li.mtop_zero Is my argument strong enough to leave out the rhetorical question?
              %li.mtop_zero Do I want to introduce a counter argument?
              %li.mtop_zero What effect will the rhetorical question create?
              %li.mtop_zero Does the question fall flat because the answer is obvious?

          %p
            It is rarely necessary to use a rhetorical question. There are usually other ways of conveying the point without using a question. If, however, you feel strongly about it, use the checklist above to confirm that your rhetorical question is contributing to your essay effectively. Each word in your essay should have a purpose, and there is nothing more problematic than having a question that does not achieve its desired effect. Nevertheless, used appropriately, the rhetorical question is an emotive device which can make reader’s question themselves and their actions.


        .preparation_col.head_aftr_none
          %h3.mtop10.mbot20#Creating_Narrative
            Creating a Narrative

          %p With a limited amount of time and a less-than-captive audience, it is important to make as big an impact as possible, as quickly as possible. This is so you distinguish yourself from the hordes of competitors and improve your chances.


          %p One way to bring colour to your writing is in forming a narrative and the use of metaphors.


          %p Humans as a part of their cognitive evolution will always seek out patterns to make sense of any information that they are presented with. More so than patterns, they will also seek out narratives to establish causal relationships.This is something that can be used to your advantage. By simply presenting your writing as a sequence of causal relationships, you will grip your reader as they seek to understand the pattern and keep reading to determine the endpoint.

          %p This can be accomplished in both creative and analytical writing. The former should be obvious, but in the latter by starting at the beginning of a chain of evidence and slowly building from causal step to causal step, your ultimate conclusion will be all the more persuasive.

        .preparation_col.head_aftr_none
          %h3.mtop10.mbot20#Using_Analogies
            Using Analogies

          %p Analogies are a great tool to help readers understand abstract or unfamiliar content. By linking abstract information to a concrete concept, it becomes easier for people to understand the information.


          %p How many times have any of us had the experience when a concept we were familiar with but never understood was explained in a slightly different or novel way, leading to an immediate, illuminating understanding – this is the power of an analogy. Whilst precision and technical language are all well and good, it can sometimes be inaccessible to those who do not have a grounding in the field. In these cases, analogies can be invaluable by couching unfamiliar concepts within familiar, or at least intuitive examples.

          %p Not only this, analogies can also be very effective for triggering emotions. This is valuable, because if people experience some elevation of emotion during their reading, not only will it make their experience more enjoyable, but also more memorable compared to the many other examples of essays. Emotions not only make your design appealing to people but also more effective, enjoyable, and memorable.

